{{Infobox character | colour = #DEDEE2 | colour text = | name = Globi | series = | image = 'Globi' in Dänikon 2012-05-13 15-59-22 (P7000).JPG | image_size = 220 | caption = | first = 1932 | last = | cause = | creator = [[Robert Lips]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.swissmint.ch/upload/_pdf/dokumentationen/medieninformationen/e/MM_05.06.2012-Kombi-e.pdf|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924112525/http://www.swissmint.ch/upload/_pdf/dokumentationen/medieninformationen/e/MM_05.06.2012-Kombi-e.pdf|dead-url= yes|archive-date= September 24, 2015|title= MM 05.06.2012-Kombi-e.pdf|accessdate= April 8, 2014}}</ref> | portrayer = | nickname = | alias = | species = Parrot | gender = Male | occupation = | title = | family = | spouse = | significantother = | children = | relatives = | religion = | nationality = Swiss }}
'''Globi''' is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[cartoon character]] occasionally referred to as Switzerland's [[Mickey Mouse]].<ref name="swissinfo1">{{cite web|author=- 15:29 |url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/archive/Swiss_Mickey_Mouse_turns_75.html?cid=666192 |title=Globi the parrot, the Swiss "Mickey Mouse", turns 75 |publisher=swissinfo.ch |date=2007-07-23 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> He is pictured as an anthropomorphic blue parrot with a yellow beak wearing a black [[beret]] and a pair of red and black checkered trousers.<ref>{{cite web|author=- 13:22 |url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/archive/Museum_honours_popular_parrot.html?cid=666120 |title=Museum honours popular parrot |publisher=swissinfo.ch |date=2003-02-01 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> He was created by the Swiss cartoonist [[Robert Lips]], as an advertising character for the Swiss department store [[Globus (company)|Globus]] in 1932 for the company's 25th anniversary. He was originally planned to be called "Kimbukku", but later renamed Globi after the local [[Swiss German|Basel German]] ''(Baseldytsch)'' dialect word for the department store that created him.<ref>{{cite web|author=- 20:03 |url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/culture/Globi_starts_going_global.html?cid=31248 |title=Popular children's cartoon character Globi appears in English translation for the first time. |publisher=swissinfo.ch |date=2009-09-25 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>
==History== He initially appeared in a cartoon strip called "Der Globi", and later appeared in a cartoon picture-book form called "Globi's World Voyage" in 1935. By 1944, the character gained so much popularity that Globus created a separate company for it, and in 1948 Globi had sold over one million picture books. He was introduced in other markets such as the [[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]] and [[Brazil]], but did not do as well. In the 1970s, he was accused of being [[sexist]], [[racist]], and promoting violence, which was based on the attitudes of the 1940s and 1950s, but the articles in question were then withdrawn and revised.<ref name="swissinfo1"/>
==Present== He is one of the most popular characters in the German-Speaking part of Switzerland, with sales of over 9 million books. However, he stays mostly unknown in the French and Italian speaking parts of the country.<ref name="rts">{{cite web|author=- 01:37 |url=https://www.rts.ch/play/radio/a-labordage/audio/les-autres-globi-star-en-suisse-alemanique-incognito-en-suisse-romande-?id=8466254&station=a9e7621504c6959e35c3ecbe7f6bed0446cdf8da |title=Les Autres: Globi, star en Suisse alémanique incognito en Suisse romande. |publisher=RTS La Première |date=2017-03-30 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>
In October 2003, a full-length film, "Globi and the Stolen Shadows" was made which was based on him. It was directed by Robi Engler in [[Anime]]-style. Beside the books, there is a lot of Globi [[merchandise]], including [[cuddly toy]]s, crockery, cutlery, clocks, school equipment, card games, food. From December 2008, the Swiss town of [[Engelberg]] hosts a Globi [[theme park]].
